Meal service will continue at the same scheduled times (see below), with one breakfast and one lunch served daily Monday through Friday. Enrollment at a FUSD school is NOT required to pick up meals.

post_text: Happy to have another community-conscious FUSD student to tell you about...American High School 9th-grader, Prisha Lakhara, recently started a local bakery business amidst the pandemic. 'Prisha's Bakery' takes orders (cakes, cookies, pretzels, etc.) via online contact, makes the items from scratch and delivers direct to customers. She is also donating 70% of the proceeds to important causes such as social justice and COVID-19.

post_text: FUSD families were notified earlier this morning. There are no students on campus and distance learning is proceeding as normal. Thank you Fremont Police Department for your assistance!
shared_text:
Fremont Police Department
September 1 at 7:46 PM ·

This morning several new anonymous bomb threat email messages were received by Fremont Unified School District schools. Our SRO team continues to work directly with FUSD and Investigations has assumed the lead on trying to identify the source. Site security walk throughs are occuring at each campus today.
The email messages are very similar in nature to those received last week and the threats are not considered credible. No children are on campus due to current distance learning protocols.

post_text: COVID-19 has brought unparalleled stress to parents as they figure out how to work from home while having their students attend school virtually. FUSD's student-run Challenge Success recently spoke with Dr. Denise Pope, co-founder of Stanford Challenge Success, on how both students and parents can work to make virtual learning successful!
shared_text:
FUSD Challenge Success
August 28 at 1:10 AM ·

Denise Pope, Ph.D. is a Senior Lecturer at Stanford University Graduate School of Education, where she specializes in student engagement and curriculum studies. As the Co-Founder of Stanford Challenge Success, she strives to provide communities with the tools needed to help students lead a healthy and balanced life. In addition to leading Challenge Success, Dr. Pope is the author of “Doing School” and is the lead author of “Overloaded and Underprepared”.

Dr. Pope lectures nationally on parenting techniques and pedagogical strategies to increase student health, engagement with learning, and integrity. Today she talks about how students and parents can work together to make learning online SUCCESSFUL.

post_text: Now there are two locations in Fremont to get out of the heat & smoke...
shared_text:
City of Fremont, CA Government
August 20 at 3:00 PM ·

The City of Fremont has opened a second Cooling/Air Quality Center. Both centers are open at the following locations during posted hours:

Warm Springs Community Center
47300 Fernald St.
10:00 a.m. to 8:00 p.m.

Fremont Community Center
40204 Paseo Padre Pkwy.
10:00 a.m. to 8:00 p.m.
(This center is within Central Park)

Facilities will adhere to social distancing practices in place during the COVID-19 pandemic. Face coverings will be required. If you arrive without one, you will be provided one from City staff.

The hours of the designated Cooling/Air Quality Centers could be adjusted based on demand as the heat/air quality conditions change throughout the week.

The City of Fremont encourages community members to check on their neighbors, the elderly, children, and those who are most vulnerable to ensure everyone is safe during this heat wave and deteriorating air quality due to current wildfires.

shared_text:
Spare the Air, Bay Area
August 20 at 2:30 PM ·

A Spare the Air Alert is in effect today, August 20 through Sunday, August 23! Burning wood, manufactured fire logs or any other solid fuel is banned, both indoors and outdoors. Protect your respiratory health and avoid exposure by staying inside with windows and doors closed until smoke levels subside, if heat is not an issue. Visit sparetheair.org for more information.

City of Fremont, CA Government
August 19 at 4:54 PM ·

The City of Fremont is opening a Cooling Center at the Warm Springs Community Center, located at 47300 Fernald St., from 10:00 a.m. to 8:00 p.m. today.

This facility will adhere to social distancing practices in place during the COVID-19 pandemic. Face coverings will be required. If you arrive without one, you will be provided with one from City staff.

At this time, the Warm Springs Community Center is the only location available today due to pre-scheduled youth camps. City staff is working on a more centralized secondary location that could be opened later in the week for additional relief.

The City of Fremont encourages community members to check on their neighbors, the elderly, children, and those who are most vulnerable to ensure everyone is safe during this heat wave and deteriorating air quality due to current wildfires.

post_text: Congratulations to American High School graduates Amber Cordero and Criselle Feria, who are recent recipients of the Kiwanis Club of Fremont Foundation's Turnaround Scholarship. The Kiwanis Turnaround Scholarship provides financial assistance and personal recognition to high school seniors who have overcome personal challenges to earn their diploma. The program is unique to Kiwanis Clubs in Silicon Valley, whose members nominate and mentor deserving students. In all the Kiwanis Club of Fremont honored 11 students from the Tri-City area. Scholarships provide $1,500 annually per student to assist with their college/trade school education.

post_text: A group of students from American, Mission San Jose and Washington High Schools have formed a nonprofit organization called Kitchen to Ward providing meals for front line healthcare workers, while simultaneously helping local businesses during COVID-19. So far, Kitchen to Ward has brought 14 healthcare centers on-board, raised over $6,000, and delivered more than 750 meals.

post_text: Starting today, use your driveway/sidewalks to encourage everyone to #BeCounted....
shared_text:
Alameda County Office of Education
July 24 at 6:54 PM ·

Show our community your commitment to being counted! Post photos of chalk art promoting participation in the 2020 Census with #ChalkTheCensusAlCo between July 27-31.

Over the past few months kids (and adults!) have shared messages of encouragement and support with art hung in front windows and chalk on sidewalks, reminding neighbors that we’re all in this together.

In that same spirit, it is the duty of everyone in our community to participate in Census 2020. A complete and accurate count of all Californians is vital in getting our fair share of federal resources that serve and uplift our entire community, including funding for schools, child nutrition, and public health services!

Please visit my2020census.gov to answer 9 simple questions (none regarding citizenship) and #BeCounted!

#YouCount #CaliforniaForAll

post_text: More Summer Camp info from City of Fremont, CA Government.....
shared_text:
City of Fremont, CA Government
June 22 at 10:45 PM ·

Fremont Recreation Services has been working diligently to revise our entire 2020 Summer Camp Program. The City of Fremont is offering a 7-week program which will include two 3-week sessions and a 1-week session for children ages 5 to 12 years old. New safety measures include:
- New camp pods of no more than 12 campers in a group
- Mandatory health screenings of all campers and staff each morning
- Expanded outdoor activities to allow for more fresh air
- Additional cleaning & sanitizing procedures
- Expanded staff safety training
- Development of a Summer COVID-19 Safety Plan outlining how each camp will operate and follows all industry and Alameda County Public Health Dept. guidelines
For more information on summer camp safety, and how to register visit www.Fremont.gov/Recreation

post_text: The Mission San Jose High School 3D Printing Club has been participating in a grassroots effort since mid-March to print face shields to help doctors and nurses during the COVID-19 crisis. MSJHS junior, Veda Chari, learned from her aunt, who is a physician, about the urgent need for face shields for front-line healthcare workers. She immediately began production by printing face shields with her 3D printer at home. Since the home printer could only print eight face shields per day, Veda contacted Dr. Brucker, the MSJHS 3D Printing Club Coordinator, who let her borrow the school’s 3D printer and filament rolls doubling the daily production of face shields. The 3D Printing Club joined the efforts of students from Cupertino's Monta Vista High School and Maker Nexus, leading to production of thousands of face shields which have been donated to healthcare facilities across the country.
text: The Mission San Jose High School 3D Printing Club has been participating in a grassroots effort since mid-March to print face shields to help doctors and nurses during the COVID-19 crisis. MSJHS junior, Veda Chari, learned from her aunt, who is a physician, about the urgent need for face shields for front-line healthcare workers. She immediately began production by printing face shields with her 3D printer at home. Since the home printer could only print eight face shields per day, Veda contacted Dr. Brucker, the MSJHS 3D Printing Club Coordinator, who let her borrow the school’s 3D printer and filament rolls doubling the daily production of face shields. The 3D Printing Club joined the efforts of students from Cupertino's Monta Vista High School and Maker Nexus, leading to production of thousands of face shields which have been donated to healthcare facilities across the country.

June 2 at 1:56 AM ·

We encourage everyone to stay safe and follow the curfew issued by counties as applicable.

Although Contra Costa County, California has not issued a formal curfew, it is still advised that residents remain indoors during this time. Learn more here: http://ow.ly/D1s150zWd0e

post_text: Important update from the Fremont Police Department...
shared_text:
Fremont Police Department
June 1 at 3:51 AM ·

Dear Fremont Community members,

We are actively monitoring the current events taking place in our region and we have increased our staffing to help ensure the safety of our community.

Alameda County has issued an advisory asking all residents to stay home at this time for their safety, due to several police incidents currently taking place in the East Bay. Please ONLY dial 911 if you have an emergency. Non-emergencies can be reported by calling 510-790-6800 x 3. Please understand there could be some delays for non-urgent matters.

During a local emergency, Nixle will be our primary communication tool. Sign up at Nixle.com or text your zip code to 888-777.

If you have a tip or information you’d like to share with us, please email Fremontpolice@fremont.gov or text your short tip to 888-777, by beginning with Tip FremontPD followed by your message.

Thank you.

post_text: The FUSD Board of Education unanimously approved two new principals for the 2020-21 school year. Warm Springs Elementary Assistant Principal Katy Carter will take over at Mission San Jose Elementary and Pamela Hughes, from Kennedy Elementary in Newark, was named Principal at Gomes Elementary. Both will assume their new roles on July 1st.

post_text: We are happy to celebrate Classified School Employee Week in recognition of all they do, both on the front lines and behind the scenes, in support of students. More to come throughout the week...
shared_text:
Alameda County Office of Education
May 18 at 4:42 PM ·

This week we're celebrating Classified School Employee Week, with an extra weight to our appreciation this year.

We have seen classified employees serving students, families and communities in an extra visible way through this pandemic, from food service to communications, technology distribution to kindergarten enrollment.

We've also seen how much we've always relied on classified employees, perhaps taking their service and impact for granted.

To all of you who support students through school, from the first day of kindergarten to high school graduation: THANK YOU! We see you and value your work more than words can express.

post_text:
Like to highlight some FUSD schools' efforts to keep in touch with their students during the Shelter-in-Place....

Maloney Elementary Principal Chris Wood has been posting his morning announcements everyday on the school's Facbeook page. Counselor Angela Tsang also checks in weekly with activities and resources for students and families.
shared_text:
Tom Maloney Elementary School was live.
May 14 at 3:36 PM ·

Good morning,
There really seems to be a theme starting to emerge with this weeks announcements. They have all been about ways to take care of yourself, and your students. Well, today is no different. I've shared with you two new posts. One from the Fremont United Student Store offering tutoring from Jr. High and High school students, and the second from Mrs. Tsang providing multiple supports for students and their families through these difficult times. We are always here for you, and more than ready to help!

6th Grade Camp Refunds:
We are in the process of completing refunds for families who paid for 6th grade science camp. You should receive a check from Fremont Unified in 2 - 3 weeks.

Grab-N-Go Lunches:
TECO Tea & Coffee (39030 Paseo Padre Pkwy): M-F, 12pm - 2pm

Subway (1980 Driscoll Road): M-F, 12pm - 1:30pm

Milk and Honey Cafe (34265 Fremont Blvd): Tu-F, 12pm – 2pm

Bombay Pizza (4922 Paseo Padre Pkwy): M-F, 12pm – 2pm

Curry Pizza (39070 Fremont Blvd): M-F, 12 – 2pm

Joe’s Corner (37713 Niles Blvd, #2946): W–F, 12pm – 2pm

post_text: Kennedy High School's AVID (Advancement Via Individual Determination) Program held its College Signing Day May 1st. Kennedy has AVID Elective classes at all four grade levels. In the elective class, students learn organizational and study skills, work on critical thinking and asking probing questions, get academic help from peers and college tutors, and participate in enrichment and motivational activities that make college attainable. Congratulations to Kennedy's AVID Class of 2020!

post_text: The California Department of Education has created a 'Help for Students in Crisis' website....
shared_text:
California Department of Education
April 21 at 5:31 PM ·

State Superintendent Tony Thurmond and the CDE are extremely concerned about the mental health and wellness of students whose lives have dramatically changed during the COVID-19 response, as well as the health of staff who are also coping with these changes.

To support students, schools, and communities during this challenging time, the CDE has gathered information regarding mental health resources, including links for students to get direct access to mental health professionals. The new “Help for Students in Crisis” web page includes crisis and warm line numbers, along with other COVID-19-related resources for providing virtual mental health services, and information for mental health providers, families, and youth: https://www.cde.ca.gov/ls/cg/mh/studentcrisishelp.asp.

post_text: FUSD students invited to participate in Virtual Art Contest. Deadline is Friday...
shared_text:
City of Fremont, CA Government
April 18 at 2:05 AM ·

To celebrate the art, creativity, and resiliency of Fremont students, the City of Fremont Human Services Department, Youth and Family Services Division in partnership with Fremont Unified School District, is hosting the third annual Children Mental Health Awareness Virtual Art Competition.

This year’s theme is “Sharing Feelings and Hope.” Students are encouraged to participate through drawing, painting, collage, photography, sculpture, creative writing, or short film. This year, students are being asked to submit their entries digitally. Finalists will be announced on Thursday, May 7, in honor of Children’s Mental Health Awareness Day.

The deadline to submit art is next Friday, April 24. For more information about the art competition or event visit www.Fremont.gov/ArtCompetition

This year’s theme is “Sharing Feelings and Hope.” Students are encouraged to participate through drawing, painting, collage, photography, sculpture, creative writing, or short film. This year, students are being asked to submit their entries digitally. Finalists will be announced on Thursday, May 7, in honor of Children’s Mental Health Awareness Day.

The deadline to submit art is next Friday, April 24. For more information about the art competition or event visit www.Fremont.gov/ArtCompetition

post_text: Thank you Fremont PD!!!!!
shared_text:
Fremont Police Department
April 19 at 5:13 AM ·

OFFICERS INCREASE PATROLS AT FREMONT SCHOOLS

Officers have increased patrols at Fremont schools after criminal groups continue to target the empty campuses. Over the last several weeks, Officers have arrested three separate groups for various crimes on these campuses. We are asking for area residents to continue reporting any suspicious activity that they may see at these schools. This includes people on campus in the middle of the night, subjects using flashlights, sounds of broken glass or forced entry, as well as any sounding alarms.

Despite the new Judicial Council of California orders to cite and release the majority of "low-level" offenders, our officers will continue to enforce all laws and protect our community. In response to these orders effect on our ability to fight crime, one of our Patrol Watch Commanders (Lt. Eric Tang) told his shift: "We'll arrest these suspects 5 times a day in order to keep our community safe if we need to."

Dani Nite is in Fremont, California.
March 27 at 2:38 AM · Instagram ·

Class class!! I have an assignment for you!! Create hearts or any art work and hang it in your windows for everyone to see. You can use colorful paper, wrapping paper, cereal boxes anything! Spread love and kindness while we are all separated and sheltering in our homes. We must stay within our homes and at a social distance (6-10 feet) while outside, BUT we can still smile and show kindness! The biggest most powerful act of kindness you can do is to stay home💜💚💙❤️💛🧡 @ Fremont, California

post_text: Bay Area school closures, including FUSD, have been extended through May 1st - http://bit.ly/3aNbsHZ. More details to come...
shared_text:
Alameda County Office of Education
March 25 at 6:01 PM ·

School closures and student dismissals from regular school attendance is extended through May 1, 2020 in Alameda, Contra Costa, Marin, San Francisco, San Mateo & Santa Clara counties to slow the spread of novel coronavirus (COVID-19).

Seven Bay Area county health officers (counties and City of Berkeley), in collaboration with their county superintendents have made this unified, regional decision for the safety and wellness of students, school personnel, and the community.

Read more: https://mailchi.mp/acoe/press-release-school-closure-extension

post_text: Everyone has a lot on their plate right now, but don't forget about Census 2020....
shared_text:
California Census 2020
March 6 at 8:35 PM ·

The #2020Census starts next Thursday, March 12th and it is a simple and confidential 9 question survey. Questions will include: name, address, sex, race, & age.

The Census will NEVER ask about your citizenship status or for your social security number, bank details, payment or a donation. Census data is not used to determine eligibility for any public programs.

#ICount
#EveryoneCounts
#CaliforniaForAll
